result.answer:
`findUser` is not clean-code-compliant as written under the command-query and hidden-side-effect guidance.

Ruling: reviewer 1 is correct on the rule. This method answers a question and also mutates object state by populating `usersById`. The fact that the mutation is an internal lazy cache does not make it a query. Under the clean-code guidance, cache population is still mutation, and here it is hidden behind a query-shaped name.

Reviewer 2 is only correct in a narrower sense: a strong-reason exception does exist, but it is explicitly an exception to command-query separation, not a case that satisfies it. If you keep the load-and-return shape, you should treat it as a deliberate tradeoff and make the mutation visible in the API, typically through naming.

Why this fails the guidance:
- `findUser` reads like a nonmutating lookup.
- The first call changes internal state; later calls can behave differently because of that state.
- That makes the mutation hidden, even if it is "harmless" and even if no external observable behavior changes beyond caching.

Smallest acceptable alternatives:

Strict CQS split:
```ts
class UserDirectory {
  private readonly usersById = new Map<string, User | undefined>();

  constructor(private readonly repository: UserRepository) {}

  loadUser(id: string): void {
    if (!this.usersById.has(id)) {
      this.usersById.set(id, this.repository.findById(id));
    }
  }

  findCachedUser(id: string): User | undefined {
    return this.usersById.get(id);
  }
}
```
This is the cleanest ruling under the guidance: one command, one query.

Smallest strong-reason exception:
```ts
class UserDirectory {
  private readonly usersById = new Map<string, User | undefined>();

  constructor(private readonly repository: UserRepository) {}

  getOrLoadUser(id: string): User | undefined {
    if (!this.usersById.has(id)) {
      this.usersById.set(id, this.repository.findById(id));
    }

    return this.usersById.get(id);
  }
}
```
This is acceptable only if you intentionally choose the exception. The important part is that the name tells the truth: it may load and mutate cache state.

Bottom line: keep `findUser` only if it is a true query. If it lazily populates cache, either split it into command plus query, or rename it to an explicit load/get-or-load form and treat that as a justified exception rather than calling it command-query separation.
